The snapshot is fully empty. I'll give you the complete, self-contained diagnosis and prescriptive fix based on the described stack, the exact symptom (36 `<strong>` spans imported verbatim from markdown scan-anchors), and standard Payload 3 / Tailwind 4 / Elan conventions.

---

## Diagnosis

Two separate problems share one root.

### Problem 1 — 36 rogue `<strong>` spans (AP-072: Semantic Markup Leaking Presentational Intent)

The source markdown used bold purely as a **scanning aid** — short imperative fragments like `**Per user.**`, `**Scaffolding.**`, `**Color.**`. These are not emphasis at all; they are informal section labels. When the content was imported into Payload CMS (Lexical editor), the importer preserved every `**…**` pair as a `bold` Lexical format node. The renderer serialises those nodes to `<strong>` which Tailwind's prose (or your Elan `prose` class) renders as `font-bold`. The result is a paragraph body that reads like a ransom note — random mid-sentence weight spikes that all compete for attention with real headings.

### Problem 2 — Flat visual hierarchy across 7 bodies (EAP-027: Missing Inter-Section Breathing Room)

Each of the 7 content blocks likely renders into a shared `<article>` with no visual separator between bodies beyond normal paragraph margin. When every block is `prose` text with no block-level punctuation (no `<hr>`, no spacing token step-up, no section heading bump), the page reads as one undifferentiated wall. The rogue bold makes this worse because faux-headings inside paragraphs train the eye to ignore actual headings.

---

## Root Cause

Two anti-patterns working in concert:

- **AP-072** — *Presentational intent smuggled through semantic markup.* The markdown author used `**bold**` for scannability, not for linguistic emphasis. The import pipeline had no normalisation step to strip or demote formatting that carries no semantic weight.
- **EAP-027** — *Missing inter-section breathing room.* The essay layout collapses 7 discrete bodies into one prose stream with no block-level breathing room — no `mt-` step-up, no `<hr>` divider token, no heading promotion — so section boundaries are invisible even without the bold pollution.

---

## Fix

There are three coordinated changes.

---

### 1. Strip the rogue bold from the Lexical data (Payload migration / seed script)

Create a one-time transform that walks every `body` rich-text tree in the ETRO essay document and removes the `bold` format from any text node whose *entire content* matches the scan-anchor pattern (short phrase, ends with `.`, no surrounding sentence context).

**`scripts/strip-scan-anchor-bold.ts`**
```ts
import payload from 'payload'
import config from '../payload.config'

// Matches the exact pattern: short label, title-cased or imperative, ends with period.
// "Per user."  "Scaffolding."  "Color."  "Typography."  etc.
const SCAN_ANCHOR_RE = /^[A-Z][a-z ]{1,30}\.$/

function stripBoldFromNode(node: Record<string, unknown>): void {
  if (node.type === 'text' && typeof node.text === 'string') {
    if (
      (node.format as number) & 1 && // bit 0 = bold in Lexical
      SCAN_ANCHOR_RE.test((node.text as string).trim())
    ) {
      node.format = (node.format as number) & ~1  // clear bold bit
    }
    return
  }
  if (Array.isArray(node.children)) {
    ;(node.children as Record<string, unknown>[]).forEach(stripBoldFromNode)
  }
}

async function run() {
  await payload.init({ config, local: true })

  const essay = await payload.find({
    collection: 'essays',        // adjust collection slug as needed
    where: { slug: { equals: 'etro' } },
    limit: 1,
  })

  const doc = essay.docs[0]
  if (!doc) throw new Error('ETRO essay not found')

  // `bodies` is an array of rich-text fields — walk each one
  const bodies: { body: Record<string, unknown> }[] = doc.bodies ?? []
  bodies.forEach(({ body }) => stripBoldFromNode(body))

  await payload.update({
    collection: 'essays',
    id: doc.id,
    data: { bodies: doc.bodies },
  })

  console.log('Done — rogue bold nodes stripped from ETRO essay.')
  process.exit(0)
}

run()
```

Run once:
```bash
npx tsx scripts/strip-scan-anchor-bold.ts
```

> **Why a targeted regex and not "strip all bold"?** The essay may contain legitimate `<strong>` use (e.g. a product name, a critical warning). The `SCAN_ANCHOR_RE` pattern (`^[A-Z][a-z ]{1,30}\.$`) is narrow enough to catch only standalone scan-anchor fragments. Review the console output before committing.

---

### 2. Harden the renderer so future imports can't re-introduce this (Lexical serialiser)

Wherever your Lexical-to-JSX serialiser handles the `bold` text format, add a context-aware guard: a text node that constitutes the *entire content* of its parent paragraph should not be rendered as `<strong>`.

**`src/components/RichText/serialise.tsx`** — find the bold branch and modify it:

```tsx
// BEFORE
if (node.format & IS_BOLD) {
  children = <strong>{children}</strong>
}

// AFTER  (AP-072 guard)
if (node.format & IS_BOLD) {
  // A text node that IS the entire paragraph paragraph is a scan-anchor, not
  // linguistic emphasis. Render as normal weight so future imports don't regress.
  const isEntireParagraph =
    parent?.children?.length === 1 &&
    parent?.type === 'paragraph'
  children = isEntireParagraph
    ? <span data-originally-bold>{children}</span>   // strip weight; keep node for debugging
    : <strong>{children}</strong>
}
```

Once you're confident no legitimate use is being swallowed, remove the `data-originally-bold` span and just emit `{children}` with no wrapper.

---

### 3. Fix the section hierarchy in the essay layout (EAP-027)

Add a visual section break between each of the 7 bodies and ensure each block's first element (likely an `h2` or `h3`) gets enough vertical separation to read as a true heading landmark.

**`src/app/(frontend)/work/etro/page.tsx`** (or wherever the essay bodies are mapped):

```tsx
// BEFORE — bodies collapsed into one prose stream
<article className="prose prose-neutral mx-auto">
  {doc.bodies.map((section) => (
    <RichText key={section.id} content={section.body} />
  ))}
</article>

// AFTER — each body is a named section with breathing room
<article className="prose prose-neutral mx-auto">
  {doc.bodies.map((section, index) => (
    <section
      key={section.id}
      aria-labelledby={`section-${index}`}
      className={index > 0 ? 'mt-16 pt-10 border-t border-neutral-200' : ''}
      // mt-16 = 64px above the rule; pt-10 = 40px below it, before the heading.
      // This uses the spacing-scale step between --spacing-14 and --spacing-20
      // in Tailwind 4's default scale — adjust to your Elan token if different.
    >
      <RichText content={section.body} />
    </section>
  ))}
</article>
```

And in your Elan prose config (or `tailwind.css` `@layer base`), make sure `h2` inside prose gets a top-margin that is meaningfully larger than `h3`, so hierarchy reads without needing bold:

```css
/* src/styles/prose.css  — Tailwind 4 @layer components */
@layer components {
  .prose h2 {
    @apply mt-14 mb-3 text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-900;
  }
  .prose h3 {
    @apply mt-8 mb-2 text-lg font-medium tracking-tight text-neutral-700;
  }
  /* Prevent strong inside prose from competing with h2/h3 */
  .prose strong {
    @apply font-semibold;   /* NOT font-bold — one step down from headings */
  }
}
```

The `font-semibold` on `strong` (vs `font-bold` on headings) preserves a visible semantic weight difference while stopping body emphasis from shouting as loudly as a heading.

---

## Principle

**Formatting should describe language structure, not substitute for it.** When a markdown author bolds a word to help themselves scan a draft, that formatting is a *writing-process artefact* — it encodes no meaning the reader needs. Importing it verbatim violates AP-072 (presentational intent leaking into semantic markup). The correct pipeline response is a normalisation pass on ingest, not a CSS workaround. Separately, seven content blocks with no structural punctuation between them is a layout anti-pattern (EAP-027): section identity must come from spacing tokens and heading hierarchy, never from in-paragraph emphasis filling the void left by absent structure. Fix the data first; fix the layout second; never use bold to do a heading's job.
